{"primaryContentSections":[{"kind":"content","content":[{"anchor":"NBKCoreKit","level":2,"type":"heading","text":"NBKCoreKit"},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"Models, protocols, and utilities underpinning this package."}]},{"anchor":"Protocols","level":3,"type":"heading","text":"Protocols"},{"type":"unorderedList","items":[{"content":[{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"reference","isActive":true,"identifier":"doc:\/\/Numberick\/documentation\/Numberick\/NBKBinaryInteger"}]}]},{"content":[{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"reference","isActive":true,"identifier":"doc:\/\/Numberick\/documentation\/Numberick\/NBKBitPatternConvertible"}]}]},{"content":[{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"reference","isActive":true,"identifier":"doc:\/\/Numberick\/documentation\/Numberick\/NBKCoreInteger"}]}]},{"content":[{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"reference","isActive":true,"identifier":"doc:\/\/Numberick\/documentation\/Numberick\/NBKFixedWidthInteger"}]}]},{"content":[{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"reference","isActive":true,"identifier":"doc:\/\/Numberick\/documentation\/Numberick\/NBKSignedInteger"}]}]},{"content":[{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"reference","isActive":true,"identifier":"doc:\/\/Numberick\/documentation\/Numberick\/NBKUnsignedInteger"}]}]}]},{"anchor":"NBKDoubleWidthKit","level":2,"type":"heading","text":"NBKDoubleWidthKit"},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"A composable, large, fixed-width, two’s complement, binary integer."}]},{"anchor":"🧩-Composable","level":3,"type":"heading","text":"🧩 Composable"},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"reference","isActive":true,"identifier":"doc:\/\/Numberick\/documentation\/Numberick\/NBKDoubleWidth"},{"type":"text","text":" is a generic software model for working with fixed-width"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"integers larger than one machine word. Its bit width is double the bit width of"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"its "},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"High"},{"type":"text","text":" component. In this way, you may construct new integer types:"}]},{"type":"codeListing","syntax":"swift","code":["typealias  Int256 = NBKDoubleWidth< Int128>","typealias UInt256 = NBKDoubleWidth<UInt128>"]},{"anchor":"💕-Twos-Complement","level":3,"type":"heading","text":"💕 Two’s Complement"},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"Like other binary integers, "},{"type":"reference","isActive":true,"identifier":"doc:\/\/Numberick\/documentation\/Numberick\/NBKDoubleWidth"},{"type":"text","text":" has two’s complement semantics."}]},{"type":"codeListing","syntax":null,"code":["The two's complement representation of  0 is an infinite sequence of 0s.","The two's complement representation of -1 is an infinite sequence of 1s."]},{"anchor":"🏰-Fixed-Width-Integer","level":3,"type":"heading","text":"🏰 Fixed-Width Integer"},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"Each type of "},{"type":"reference","isActive":true,"identifier":"doc:\/\/Numberick\/documentation\/Numberick\/NBKDoubleWidth"},{"type":"text","text":" has a fixed bit width, and so do its halves."},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"This design comes with a suite of overflow and bit-casting operations. The"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"even split also lends itself to divide-and-conquer strategies. As such, it"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"leverages A. Karatsuba’s multiplication algorithm, as well as C. Burnikel’s"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"and J. Ziegler’s fast recursive division."}]},{"anchor":"📖-Trivial-UInt-Collection","level":3,"type":"heading","text":"📖 Trivial UInt Collection"},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"reference","isActive":true,"identifier":"doc:\/\/Numberick\/documentation\/Numberick\/NBKDoubleWidth"},{"type":"text","text":" models a trivial "},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"UInt"},{"type":"text","text":" collection, where "},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"UInt"},{"type":"text","text":" is an"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"unsigned machine word. It contains at least two words, but the exact count"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"depends on the platform’s architecture. You should, therefore, use"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"properties like "},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"startIndex"},{"type":"text","text":" and "},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"endIndex"},{"type":"text","text":" instead of hard-coded indices."}]},{"type":"codeListing","syntax":null,"code":["\/\/ Int256 and UInt256, as constructed on a 64-bit platform:","┌───────────────────────────┐ ┌───────────────────────────┐","│           Int256          │ │          UInt256          │","├─────────────┬─────────────┤ ├─────────────┬─────────────┤","│    Int128   │   UInt128   │ │   UInt128   │   UInt128   │","├──────┬──────┼──────┬──────┤ ├──────┬──────┼──────┬──────┤","│  Int │ UInt │ UInt │ UInt │ │ UInt │ UInt │ UInt │ UInt │","└──────┴──────┴──────┴──────┘ └──────┴──────┴──────┴──────┘"]},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"Swift’s type system enforces proper layout insofar as "},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"Int"},{"type":"text","text":" and "},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"UInt"},{"type":"text","text":" are the"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"only types in the standard library that meet its type requirements."},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"Specifically, only "},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"Int"},{"type":"text","text":" and "},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"UInt"},{"type":"text","text":" have "},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"NBKCoreInteger<UInt>"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"Digit"},{"type":"text","text":" types."}]},{"anchor":"🚀-Single-Digit-Arithmagick","level":3,"type":"heading","text":"🚀 Single Digit Arithmagick"},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"Alongside its ordinary arithmagick operations, "},{"type":"reference","isActive":true,"identifier":"doc:\/\/Numberick\/documentation\/Numberick\/NBKDoubleWidth"},{"type":"text","text":" provides"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"single-digit operations, where a digit is an un\/signed machine word. These"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"operations are more efficient for small calculations. Here are some examples:"}]},{"type":"codeListing","syntax":"swift","code":["Int256(1) + Int(1), UInt256(1) + UInt(1)","Int256(2) - Int(2), UInt256(2) - UInt(2)","Int256(3) * Int(3), UInt256(3) * UInt(3)","Int256(4) \/ Int(4), UInt256(4) \/ UInt(4)","Int256(5) % Int(5), UInt256(5) % UInt(5)"]},{"style":"note","content":[{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"The "},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"Digit"},{"type":"text","text":" type is "},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"Int"},{"type":"text","text":" when "},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"Self"},{"type":"text","text":" is signed, and "},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"UInt"},{"type":"text","text":" otherwise."}]}],"type":"aside","name":"Note"}]}],"schemaVersion":{"major":0,"minor":3,"patch":0},"sections":[],"variants":[{"paths":["\/documentation\/numberick"],"traits":[{"interfaceLanguage":"swift"}]}],"identifier":{"url":"doc:\/\/Numberick\/documentation\/Numberick","interfaceLanguage":"swift"},"abstract":[{"type":"text","text":"Large number arithmagick in Swift."}],"kind":"symbol","metadata":{"roleHeading":"Framework","externalID":"Numberick","title":"Numberick","symbolKind":"module","role":"collection","modules":[{"name":"Numberick"}]},"hierarchy":{"paths":[[]]},"topicSections":[{"title":"Protocols","identifiers":["doc:\/\/Numberick\/documentation\/Numberick\/NBKBinaryInteger","doc:\/\/Numberick\/documentation\/Numberick\/NBKBitPatternConvertible","doc:\/\/Numberick\/documentation\/Numberick\/NBKCoreInteger","doc